    <div class="explanation">
        <h2>Why Bubble Sort is rarely the "best" choice:</h2>
        <p>While simple to understand and implement, Bubble Sort is notoriously inefficient for most practical applications. Here's a breakdown:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Time Complexity (O(n²)):</strong> This means that as the number of items (n) to sort doubles, the time it takes to sort them quadruples. For even moderately sized datasets (e.g., thousands of items), it becomes incredibly slow.</li>
            <li><strong>High Number of Swaps/Comparisons:</strong> As you'll observe in the animation, Bubble Sort performs many comparisons and swaps, even for elements that are far from their final sorted position. It repeatedly "bubbles up" the largest elements to their correct place.</li>
            <li><strong>Limited Practical Use:</strong> Its only real advantage is its simplicity and perhaps for extremely small, nearly sorted datasets where its O(n) best-case complexity (if already sorted) might be marginally relevant, but even then, other algorithms like Insertion Sort often outperform it due to lower constant factors.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Understanding Time Complexity (Big O Notation):</h2>
        <p>Big O notation describes how the runtime or space requirements of an algorithm grow as the input size (n) grows. It focuses on the upper bound of the growth rate.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>O(1) - Constant Time:</strong> The operation takes the same amount of time regardless of input size. (e.g., accessing an array element by index).</li>
            <li><strong>O(log n) - Logarithmic Time:</strong> The time grows very slowly as input size increases. Often seen in algorithms that repeatedly halve the problem size. (e.g., binary search).</li>
            <li><strong>O(n) - Linear Time:</strong> The time grows proportionally to the input size. (e.g., iterating through an array once).</li>
            <li><strong>O(n log n) - "Linearithmic" Time:</strong> This is generally considered the optimal complexity for comparison-based sorting algorithms. It's much faster than O(n²) for large n. (e.g., Merge Sort, Quick Sort (average case)).</li>
            <li><strong>O(n²) - Quadratic Time:</strong> The time grows as the square of the input size. Algorithms with nested loops iterating over the data often fall into this category. (e.g., Bubble Sort, Selection Sort, Insertion Sort (worst/average case)).</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Key Takeaway:</strong> For larger datasets, algorithms with O(n log n) complexity like Merge Sort and Quick Sort are vastly superior to O(n²) algorithms like Bubble Sort. The difference in performance becomes monumental as 'n' increases.</p>
