    <div class="complexity-explanation">
        <h2>Why Bubble Sort is NOT the Best for Everything</h2>
        <p>
            The claim that Bubble Sort is the "best sorting algorithm for everything" is fundamentally flawed. While simple to understand and implement, its performance degrades drastically as the amount of data increases. This visual demonstration highlights this inefficiency by comparing it against two generally much faster algorithms: Merge Sort and Quick Sort.
        </p>

        <h3>Understanding Algorithm Complexity (Big O Notation)</h3>
        <p>
            Algorithm complexity, often expressed using Big O notation (e.g., <code>O(n)</code>, <code>O(n log n)</code>, <code>O(n^2)</code>), describes how the runtime or space requirements of an algorithm grow as the input size (<code>n</code>) increases.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><code>O(1)</code>: Constant time. The time taken doesn't depend on the input size.</li>
            <li><code>O(log n)</code>: Logarithmic time. Time increases very slowly with input size.</li>
            <li><code>O(n)</code>: Linear time. Time increases proportionally to the input size.</li>
            <li><code>O(n log n)</code>: "Linearithmic" time. Efficient for large datasets, typical for good comparison sorts.</li>
            <li><code>O(n^2)</code>: Quadratic time. Time increases as the square of the input size. This is generally considered inefficient for large inputs.</li>
            <li><code>O(2^n)</code>, <code>O(n!)</code>: Exponential/Factorial time. Extremely inefficient, only practical for very small inputs.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Bubble Sort</h3>
        <p>
            <strong>Best Case:</strong> <code>O(n)</code> (Array is already sorted) <br>
            <strong>Average Case:</strong> <code>O(n^2)</code> <br>
            <strong>Worst Case:</strong> <code>O(n^2)</code> (Array is reverse sorted)
        </p>
        <p>
            Bubble Sort repeatedly steps through the list, compares adjacent elements and swaps them if they are in the wrong order. The pass through the list is repeated until no swaps are needed, which indicates that the list is sorted. Its quadratic complexity means that if you double the number of elements, the sorting time roughly quadruples. This makes it impractical for large datasets.
        </p>

        <h3>Merge Sort</h3>
        <p>
            <strong>Best Case:</strong> <code>O(n log n)</code> <br>
            <strong>Average Case:</strong> <code>O(n log n)</code> <br>
            <strong>Worst Case:</strong> <code>O(n log n)</code>
        </p>
        <p>
            Merge Sort is a "divide and conquer" algorithm. It recursively divides the array into two halves until it gets to single-element arrays (which are inherently sorted). Then, it repeatedly merges these sorted sub-arrays to produce new sorted sub-arrays until there is only one sorted array remaining. Its consistent <code>O(n log n)</code> performance makes it a very stable and reliable choice for various applications.
        </p>

        <h3>Quick Sort</h3>
        <p>
            <strong>Best Case:</strong> <code>O(n log n)</code> <br>
            <strong>Average Case:</strong> <code>O(n log n)</code> <br>
            <strong>Worst Case:</strong> <code>O(n^2)</code> (Poor pivot choice, e.g., already sorted or reverse sorted array)
        </p>
        <p>
            Quick Sort is another "divide and conquer" algorithm. It works by selecting a 'pivot' element from the array and partitioning the other elements into two sub-arrays, according to whether they are less than or greater than the pivot. The sub-arrays are then sorted recursively. While its worst-case scenario is <code>O(n^2)</code>, its average-case performance of <code>O(n log n)</code> is excellent, and it's often faster in practice than Merge Sort due to better cache performance and fewer data movements.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>Conclusion:</strong> For general-purpose sorting, Merge Sort and Quick Sort (or hybrid algorithms like Python's Timsort or Java's Dual-Pivot Quicksort) are vastly superior to Bubble Sort due to their significantly better average-case time complexities. Bubble Sort might have niche uses for extremely small arrays or educational purposes, but it's far from "the best for everything."
        </p>
    </div>

    <script>
        const ARRAY_MAX_HEIGHT = 200; // Max height for bars in pixels
        let ARRAY_SIZE = 50;
        let ANIMATION_SPEED_MS = 50; // Milliseconds per animation step

        let originalArray = [];
        let sorting = false;
        let timeouts = [];

        // DOM Elements
        const bubbleSortContainer = document.getElementById('bubbleSortContainer');
        const mergeSortContainer = document.getElementById('mergeSortContainer');
        const quickSortContainer = document.getElementById('quickSortContainer');
        const bubbleSortStepsSpan = document.getElementById('bubbleSortSteps');
        const mergeSortStepsSpan = document.getElementById('mergeSortSteps');
        const quickSortStepsSpan = document.getElementById('quickSortSteps');
        const generateArrayBtn = document.getElementById('generateArray');
        const startSortBtn = document.getElementById('startSort');
        const resetBtn = document.getElementById('reset');
        const arraySizeSlider = document.getElementById('arraySize');
        const arraySizeValueSpan = document.getElementById('arraySizeValue');
        const animationSpeedSlider = document.getElementById('animationSpeed');
        const animationSpeedValueSpan = document.getElementById('animationSpeedValue');

        // Event Listeners
        generateArrayBtn.addEventListener('click', generateNewArray);
        startSortBtn.addEventListener('click', startSorting);
        resetBtn.addEventListener('click', resetVisualization);
        arraySizeSlider.addEventListener('input', (e) => {
            ARRAY_SIZE = parseInt(e.target.value);
            arraySizeValueSpan.textContent = ARRAY_SIZE;
            resetVisualization(); // Reset and generate new array with new size
        });
        animationSpeedSlider.addEventListener('input', (e) => {
            ANIMATION_SPEED_MS = parseInt(e.target.value);
            animationSpeedValueSpan.textContent = ANIMATION_SPEED_MS;
        });

        // --- Utility Functions ---
        function generateRandomArray() {
            const array = [];
            for (let i = 0; i < ARRAY_SIZE; i++) {
                array.push(Math.floor(Math.random() * (ARRAY_MAX_HEIGHT - 10)) + 10); // Min height 10px
            }
            return array;
        }

        function createBars(container, array) {
            container.innerHTML = ''; // Clear existing bars
            const barWidth = Math.max(2, Math.floor((container.clientWidth - (ARRAY_SIZE * 2)) / ARRAY_SIZE)); // Calculate width dynamically
            array.forEach((value, index) => {
                const bar = document.createElement('div');
                bar.classList.add('bar');
                bar.style.height = `${value}px`;
                bar.style.width = `${barWidth}px`;
                bar.dataset.value = value; // Store original value for reference
                container.appendChild(bar);
            });
        }

        function updateBarColors(container, indices, className, clearPrevious = false) {
            const bars = container.children;
            if (clearPrevious) {
                for (let i = 0; i < bars.length; i++) {
                    bars[i].classList.remove('comparing', 'swapping', 'sorted', 'pivot', 'partitioning');
                }
            }
            indices.forEach(index => {
                if (bars[index]) {
                    bars[index].classList.add(className);
                }
            });
        }

        function removeBarColors(container, indices, className) {
            const bars = container.children;
            indices.forEach(index => {
                if (bars[index]) {
                    bars[index].classList.remove(className);
                }
            });
        }

        function swapBars(container, index1, index2) {
            const bars = container.children;
            const bar1 = bars[index1];
            const bar2 = bars[index2];

            // Swap heights
            const h1 = bar1.style.height;
            bar1.style.height = bar2.style.height;
            bar2.style.height = h1;

            // Optional: Swap data-value if needed for debugging
            const v1 = bar1.dataset.value;
            bar1.dataset.value = bar2.dataset.value;
            bar2.dataset.value = v1;
        }

        function highlightSorted(container, index) {
            const bars = container.children;
            if (bars[index]) {
                bars[index].classList.remove('comparing', 'swapping', 'pivot', 'partitioning');
                bars[index].classList.add('sorted');
            }
        }

        function clearAllTimeouts() {
            timeouts.forEach(clearTimeout);
            timeouts = [];
        }

        function generateNewArray() {
            if (sorting) return;
            originalArray = generateRandomArray();
            resetVisualization(false); // Don't generate new if resetting
            createBars(bubbleSortContainer, originalArray);
            createBars(mergeSortContainer, originalArray);
            createBars(quickSortContainer, originalArray);
            bubbleSortStepsSpan.textContent = 0;
            mergeSortStepsSpan.textContent = 0;
            quickSortStepsSpan.textContent = 0;
        }

        function resetVisualization(shouldGenerate = true) {
            clearAllTimeouts();
            sorting = false;
            if (shouldGenerate) {
                generateNewArray();
            } else {
                createBars(bubbleSortContainer, originalArray);
                createBars(mergeSortContainer, originalArray);
                createBars(quickSortContainer, originalArray);
                bubbleSortStepsSpan.textContent = 0;
                mergeSortStepsSpan.textContent = 0;
                quickSortStepsSpan.textContent = 0;
            }
            // Ensure all bars are reset to default color
            [bubbleSortContainer, mergeSortContainer, quickSortContainer].forEach(container => {
                Array.from(container.children).forEach(bar => {
                    bar.classList.remove('comparing', 'swapping', 'sorted', 'pivot', 'partitioning');
                });
            });
        }

        function startSorting() {
            if (sorting) return;
            sorting = true;
            resetVisualization(false); // Use existing array
            startSortBtn.disabled = true;
            generateArrayBtn.disabled = true;
            arraySizeSlider.disabled = true;

            const bubbleArray = [...originalArray];
            const mergeArray = [...originalArray];
            const quickArray = [...originalArray];

            // Run sorts
            visualizeBubbleSort(bubbleArray, bubbleSortContainer, bubbleSortStepsSpan);
            visualizeMergeSort(mergeArray, mergeSortContainer, mergeSortStepsSpan);
            visualizeQuickSort(quickArray, quickSortContainer, quickSortStepsSpan);
        }

        // --- Sorting Algorithms with Visualization ---

        // Bubble Sort
        async function visualizeBubbleSort(array, container, stepCounterSpan) {
            let steps = 0;
            let n = array.length;
            for (let i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
                for (let j = 0; j < n - i - 1; j++) {
                    steps++;
                    stepCounterSpan.textContent = steps;

                    updateBarColors(container, [j, j + 1], 'comparing');
                    await new Promise(resolve => timeouts.push(setTimeout(resolve, ANIMATION_SPEED_MS)));

                    if (array[j] > array[j + 1]) {
                        updateBarColors(container, [j, j + 1], 'swapping');
                        await new Promise(resolve => timeouts.push(setTimeout(resolve, ANIMATION_SPEED_MS)));

                        [array[j], array[j + 1]] = [array[j + 1], array[j]]; // Swap in logic array
                        swapBars(container, j, j + 1); // Swap in visual

                        await new Promise(resolve => timeouts.push(setTimeout(resolve, ANIMATION_SPEED_MS)));
                    }
                    removeBarColors(container, [j, j + 1], 'comparing');
                    removeBarColors(container, [j, j + 1], 'swapping');
                }
                highlightSorted(container, n - 1 - i); // Mark the largest element as sorted
            }
            highlightSorted(container, 0); // Mark the last element as sorted
            signalSortComplete();
        }

        // Merge Sort
        async function visualizeMergeSort(array, container, stepCounterSpan) {
            let steps = 0;
            const auxArray = [...array]; // Auxiliary array for merging

            async function merge(arr, start, mid, end) {
                let i = start;
                let j = mid + 1;
                let k = start;

                while (i <= mid && j <= end) {
                    steps++;
                    stepCounterSpan.textContent = steps;
                    updateBarColors(container, [i, j], 'comparing');
                    await new Promise(resolve => timeouts.push(setTimeout(resolve, ANIMATION_SPEED_MS)));

                    if (arr[i] <= arr[j]) {
                        auxArray[k] = arr[i];
                        i++;
                    } else {
                        auxArray[k] = arr[j];
                        j++;
                    }
                    // Update the bar in the main container to reflect the auxArray move
                    // This is a simplified visual representation for merge sort's aux array copy
                    // A more accurate visual would show a separate aux array, but this is simpler
                    const bars = container.children;
                    bars[k].style.height = `${auxArray[k]}px`;
                    bars[k].classList.add('partitioning'); // Indicate it's part of the merge process
                    await new Promise(resolve => timeouts.push(setTimeout(resolve, ANIMATION_SPEED_MS / 2)));
                    removeBarColors(container, [i - 1, j - 1], 'comparing'); // Clear previous comparing
                    k++;
                }

                while (i <= mid) {
                    steps++;
                    stepCounterSpan.textContent = steps;
                    auxArray[k] = arr[i];
                    const bars = container.children;
                    bars[k].style.height = `${auxArray[k]}px`;
                    bars[k].classList.add('partitioning');
                    await new Promise(resolve => timeouts.push(setTimeout(resolve, ANIMATION_SPEED_MS / 2)));
                    i++;
                    k++;
                }

                while (j <= end) {
                    steps++;
                    stepCounterSpan.textContent = steps;
                    auxArray[k] = arr[j];
                    const bars = container.children;
                    bars[k].style.height = `${auxArray[k]}px`;
                    bars[k].classList.add('partitioning');
                    await new Promise(resolve => timeouts.push(setTimeout(resolve, ANIMATION_SPEED_MS / 2)));
                    j++;
                    k++;
                }

                for (let l = start; l <= end; l++) {
                    arr[l] = auxArray[l];
                    const bars = container.children;
                    bars[l].style.height = `${arr[l]}px`;
                    bars[l].classList.remove('partitioning'); // Remove partitioning color after placing
                    // No await here for individual bar updates for performance, only for the main merge step
                }
                // Highlight merged section as temporary sorted
                updateBarColors(container, Array.from({length: end - start + 1}, (_, i) => start + i), 'sorted');
                await new Promise(resolve => timeouts.push(setTimeout(resolve, ANIMATION_SPEED_MS)));
                removeBarColors(container, Array.from({length: end - start + 1}, (_, i) => start + i), 'sorted'); // Remove temp sorted
            }

            async function mergeSort(arr, start, end) {
                if (start >= end) {
                    return;
                }
                const mid = Math.floor((start + end) / 2);
                await mergeSort(arr, start, mid);
                await mergeSort(arr, mid + 1, end);
                await merge(arr, start, mid, end);
            }

            await mergeSort(array, 0, array.length - 1);
            // Mark all as sorted at the end
            for (let i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {
                highlightSorted(container, i);
            }
            signalSortComplete();
        }

        // Quick Sort
        async function visualizeQuickSort(array, container, stepCounterSpan) {
            let steps = 0;

            async function partition(arr, low, high) {
                const pivot = arr[high];
                let i = low - 1;

                updateBarColors(container, [high], 'pivot');
                await new Promise(resolve => timeouts.push(setTimeout(resolve, ANIMATION_SPEED_MS)));

                for (let j = low; j < high; j++) {
                    steps++;
                    stepCounterSpan.textContent = steps;
                    updateBarColors(container, [j], 'comparing');
                    await new Promise(resolve => timeouts.push(setTimeout(resolve, ANIMATION_SPEED_MS)));

                    if (arr[j] < pivot) {
                        i++;
                        updateBarColors(container, [i, j], 'swapping');
                        await new Promise(resolve => timeouts.push(setTimeout(resolve, ANIMATION_SPEED_MS)));

                        [arr[i], arr[j]] = [arr[j], arr[i]];
                        swapBars(container, i, j);

                        await new Promise(resolve => timeouts.push(setTimeout(resolve, ANIMATION_SPEED_MS)));
                        removeBarColors(container, [i, j], 'swapping');
                    }
                    removeBarColors(container, [j], 'comparing');
                }

                removeBarColors(container, [high], 'pivot'); // Clear pivot color before final swap
                updateBarColors(container, [i + 1, high], 'swapping');
                await new Promise(resolve => timeouts.push(setTimeout(resolve, ANIMATION_SPEED_MS)));

                [arr[i + 1], arr[high]] = [arr[high], arr[i + 1]];
                swapBars(container, i + 1, high);

                await new Promise(resolve => timeouts.push(setTimeout(resolve, ANIMATION_SPEED_MS)));
                removeBarColors(container, [i + 1, high], 'swapping');

                highlightSorted(container, i + 1); // Mark pivot's final position as sorted
                return i + 1;
            }

            async function quickSort(arr, low, high) {
                if (low < high) {
                    let pi = await partition(arr, low, high);
                    await quickSort(arr, low, pi - 1);
                    await quickSort(arr, pi + 1, high);
                } else if (low === high) { // Single element is considered sorted
                    highlightSorted(container, low);
                }
            }

            await quickSort(array, 0, array.length - 1);
            // Ensure all bars are marked sorted in case of edge cases or small arrays
            for (let i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {
                highlightSorted(container, i);
            }
            signalSortComplete();
        }

        let completedSorts = 0;
        function signalSortComplete() {
            completedSorts++;
            if (completedSorts === 3) { // All 3 sorts are done
                sorting = false;
                startSortBtn.disabled = false;
                generateArrayBtn.disabled = false;
                arraySizeSlider.disabled = false;
                completedSorts = 0; // Reset for next run
            }
        }

        // Initial setup
        generateNewArray();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
